Combat armed hand: the MP3 player against the mobile.
We advise you how to choose.
While almost every mobile player plays MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls.
What seems clear is that it is better to buy only the phone.
Yet there are enough reasons for man to acquire only the reproducer.
The choice practically depends on the way of its use and the demand of the future owner.
Probably it will be hard to acquire the most modern tocadiscos to listen to Maxim Turbulenc’s latest album.
On the other hand, this type of music products such as LPs no longer come out, and as far as their quality is concerned, there is no single objective reason to continue buying them.
If you pick up vinyl discs with art rock, jazz or blues music on your shelves, you are probably dreaming, at least, of this type of disc.
This is the same with the music that is on the go, that is, compressed, simplified music – MP3 music.
And here there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, the same as for a Pink Floyd lover who will hardly try the twenty crowns market helmets.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for each.
The choice is wide.
It also determines the battery life.
Some of the best players much more than just playing music and even what not even most mobile phones.
No device today is as universal as the phone.
In front of the most elementary functions such as telephoning, sending messages, you can play music and video, record both, have a better or worse camera and even you can get to browse.
And when we consider the Smartphone and PDAs will also have a small computer in their pocket.
This is a small miracle as no refrigerator can make a grille and no television can photograph.
The universality of mobile phones also brings us disadvantages.
The more functions you use on the mobile, the sooner the screen indicator will light up asking to be recharged.
And music reproduction is one of the greatest sources of energy.
Few mobile phones can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, most of them much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest ones) have clearly higher performance.
Therefore, keep in mind that cheap mobile phones will not play for more than two hours.
If in addition to this, above all, they constantly call still, for more security, a charger for work - this is also true for the more expensive appliances.
With the MP3 player this problem will not be, since even the worst can withstand at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation after a charge.
Another problem occurs when recording music on the mobile.
Unfortunately, only a part of the devices have the universal USB connector and, in addition, not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course it is possible to record music directly on the memory card but only on some units without reduction can connect the small memory cards that are used on mobile phones.
On players, with some exceptions (iPod), no special software is required.
Just fill the device with music via the USB of the computer.
Most mobile phones and players create their own order in the music library according to the name of the performer, album title, genre or also according to user rating.
Some devices only show a directory with a tree structure similar to a Windows Search and some recognize both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
The player tries to serve, the mobile knows more
For the choice of a particular equipment, you are interested in the strength of the accumulator, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the convenience of its handling.
If you listen, above all, to the music as a background and will listen to it every day only for a while, like in the tram, then it is enough with any mobile that you play.
This is what practically any mobile can.
You should not even be interested in the format in which the mobile phone or player plays the music.
The MP3 is played by everyone and almost all the music that comes to you will be in this format.
It is among the most widespread and except for it the absolute majority of the devices play music in WMA format.
The least include the AAC format (format used by the company Apple and its iPod).
The best mobile devices also enable, for example, the purchase of music online.
It is enough to visit the competent pages of the operator (or any other service provider) and buy a song or album.
This service could be in itself just a weight argument to acquire a mobile for music.
Unfortunately the offer of the operators is miserable and the majority is limited only to the flying success themes of the radios.
Prices are also not the lowest.
However, in general, it is supposed that precisely this way of selling music (whether by GSM, internet or wireless internet) in the future will dominate the music industry.
Most people always carry a cell phone.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you will find the mobile phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player will be forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry a headphone or, at least, handsfree.
If not, you can use an integrated player that has virtually every mobile even if it is at least an MP3 player.
Probably the biggest advantage for many of the mobile phones with music will be their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
Between three and four thousand crowns can already purchase a good walkman.
Most of you will limit the absence of an entry for classic headphones.
The best, even in terms of the technical part, such as phones equipped with an input of 3.5 mm. for classic headphones, cost up to fifteen thousand.
Again, the advantage of players is nothing more than their easy service.
The simplest players – not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) – are managed by really anyone.
The minimal functions, their handling similar to the previous current casets or also to the touchdiscs is evident.
It does not represent a threat in the sense that by mistake we connect to the internet with the mobile and, consequently, gigantic account for data downloading.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (for example, the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for changing the memory card (M2 type, micro SD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of a suitable card will reach two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models are usually equipped with only a 2 GB maximum capacity card.
Only the most expensive have a memory of 8 GB.
If you already have a mobile phone and you still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a look at Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
According to the capacity (maximum 2 GB) it is not necessary to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are considered among the most demanding lovers of music, use the most specialized mobile-walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have independent keys for MP3 which makes a service as convenient as that of a single player.
The most specialized of all is Sony Ericsson, whose walkman line phones have almost identical use as that of an independent MP3 player.
The same service and the same category in terms of price, over four thousand crowns, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery capacity (usually 15 hours, with a maximum performance of up to 35 hours), the above-mentioned brand brings them MP3 players.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all the services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still miss something – the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It will probably not take long to arrive.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the entire Union.
After the latest steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges it is likely to come to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to fight.
Probably this seems paradoxical to us, since we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
Pavel Dvořák, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), also said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is true that for a classic operator with its own network it no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still one possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a prominent price decline before which the classic operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before shark such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for this type of operators and that they can succeed.
There is no need to look for examples too far.
In February this year we informed you about the debut of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking is the Penta group that, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual traders is the ability to focus on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order for them to operate effectively, they are enough with much fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not involve relatively large expenses in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, this type of virtual operators are typically profiled with low costs – they offer cheap calls and SMS messages which, however, is often contrasted with the offer of more tailored services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheap as compared to the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good hit to bet on a no trivial target group.
It is specifically directed to the man.
“The right man chooses Mobilking – it’s the operator you like and who you can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works with this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say if a similar concept like that of Poland could get stuck in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický said: “The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators rely.
In addition, from the point of view of the service supply is relatively saturated.”
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it doesn't seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region,” said Jana Studničková, a spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, in a phone call to mobil.cz.
He indirectly assured that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Rather, on the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
“We have a great interest in this, in order to be able to offer our customers not only fixed phone services but also mobile phone services.
The sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly encountered all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have managed to move forward in the meetings," said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe there are better times.
It seems to be that, by unofficial information, the first official operator would have to arrive possibly already at the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At this moment we believe that the situation is suitable for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project on this ground,” Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2, told mobil.cz.
Other operators refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accord with O2's opinion, adds: "Until today we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to develop."
He added: “In T-Mobile’s network, it will be difficult to find any virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this point we should already have on the table some concrete contract that would be possible to study in such a short time."
Vodafone focuses its attention on fulfilling the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický adds: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of spending and infrastructure sharing.
We consider it to be the biggest contribution from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area lies in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on the mobile.”
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, which would lead to a drop in prices and thus a drop in profits.
So why facilitate entrance to competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to shoot from the same rope, proof of this is the grip when U:fon appeared.
Per the biggest pressure on the ČTÚ was at the time of the entry of U:fon by T-Mobile.
This is attested by public information available on the ČTÚ website.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for why not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds: “In addition, not long ago, the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was opened to a fourth operator.
As regards the character of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would be very demanding for him and, above all, for his services.”
That is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the ČTU’s position, which unfortunately has no competition to intervene in commercial bidding, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Procurement (ÚOHS).
However, she expressed her typical stance on this problem.
“The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator was concluded.
So far, no agreement has been closed since the offer of the potential interested parties was not interesting enough for the classic operators,” added Kristián Chalupa, of the UOHS Foreign Relations Department.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For offices that should represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, besides that they should observe that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In abroad where virtual operators work normally we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to the fall in prices of mobile phone services"
Obviously, pressure on the proper functioning of the market means and the fall in prices do not fall within the interests of the OHSS.
Really the dramatically shocking thing in this whole case lies in the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether this really is a coincidence, is offered by itself.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in the gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and of a tough struggle for competition.
“The Office in this sense has not found signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the traders has a dominant position and therefore do not have a corresponding rise in responsibility in their actions in the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are lacking, as are telecommunications regulators,” Chalupa added to his response.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many conflicting points.
Evidently, there is a relevant market analysis by the ČTÚ according to which telecommunications is, from the point of view of commercial bidding, a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another approach - in order for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary the agreement with the network administrator.
And the mobile operator – with all its logic – has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for ÚOHS should represent a warning the fact that three mobile operators rise strikingly in a similar way.
Current complaints from stakeholders (including the aforementioned GTS Novera company) show that in all negotiations with operators many similar impediments are encountered.
Carrying responsibility on the ČTÚ is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the ÚOHS washes its hands in all this matter.
We have already met him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law was recently submitted to expand the ČTÚ’s competition in the field of commercial tenders, which did not take effect, even when a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This should be well-known to UOHS representatives, but it is obvious that their interests lie elsewhere.
Everything is fine when no one looks.
At the same time, unnoticedly continues to work something like a pseudovirtual operator that in the Czech mobile phone networks already exists a few.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile phone services that, however, only part are public.
These are usually companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile services.
Usually only a few selected people get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a lot of SIM cards.
As a special customer, you will receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that the business conditions at all Czech mobile operators prohibit this type of resale.
"If cases like those mentioned were discovered, we could talk about breach of contract terms that could result in the end of the collaboration with the given society," Martina Kemrová said.
But it is quite unlikely that an activity of this type carried out by mobile operators will not reach responsible people.
In the case of the three companies mentioned above, thousands of customers can be dealt with.
None of the operators are opposed to this procedure.
Through the activities of these companies they earn no negligible profits and, at the same time - unlike authentic virtual traders - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the possible problems: "the law allows for this kind of speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a disproportionate percent of customers.
These, in addition, must accept that their phone’s SIM card is not in their name so they can’t possibly dispose of it as a regular customer of the operators.”
This is precisely what should seem to the ČTÚ at least strange.
There is also a new question for the UOHS.
If mobile operators are turning their eyes around in this type of procedure, why are they blocking the entrance of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want it, it should not be content with the operators' explanations that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive?
As was already clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant drop in the prices of services.
At the same time, virtually in every country where the virtual operator emerged, the classic operators tried to more or less protect themselves from this break-up.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical – too small, a market eventually too saturated, problems with service quality, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, at this time the regulatory bodies have intervened and in none of the cases defended the operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the emergence of the first virtual operator and with it began to emerge others.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body passes this whole case as if it were a burning clove.
By our experience we cannot fail to impress that the confusion of attributions in these cases suits them.
But let us not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator actually arrives in these lands, then the Czech mobile market is probably starting to move again.
If any of the operators let some virtual mobile phone operator enter, it will be difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling it more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four presentations of the new version of the official Czech anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the day of the official Czech celebrations presented the new official recording of the national anthem Where, my home.
The new anthem was recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one with male voice and another with female voice, another with Choir and another instrumental.
The song is performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the arrangements of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the server iHNed.cz you can listen to the four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this national Czech hymn to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
The Czech Radio said earlier that it intentionally chose singers with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
“From the beginning I tried with the two and then, too, with the Choir to fix on the diction so that the text was well understood, so that it had consonance,” he said.
The Czech National Anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, My Home sounded for the first time in the year 1834 on the tables of the Theatre of the States in the original Czech work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people made it theirs.
The first strofe of the song after the emergence of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became, naturally, a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
