Prague MHD takes us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, the date is written into the history of the Prague Transport Company when the first passengers enter the metro, tram and bus with an electronic voucher in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
It can now be purchased by 100,000 people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase the 30-day, 90-day and annual voucher (it will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously load it on their chip card at the transport company’s infocenters and stations at the Metro, Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka stations.
The bonds can be purchased on the internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by over 400 people.
Those who start using the internet as a form of trading can start to forget about the ticket stations at the metro stations, where until now they had to regularly catch a regular ticket.
The bonus is purchased on the internet, and the Opencard card is charged in one of the thirteen branches of the Municipal Library.
“In these places there is a window with prepared staff available to passengers that helps interested parties with online shopping and also with charging the voucher purchased on their card,” said Martin Opatrný, spokesman for the project.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to recharge the electronic voucher on the Opencard on the dealer machines that are located in some metro halls.
How are these expenditure machines?
They are red, they remind us of a ticketing machine and travelers will probably have already looked at them at the metro stations of Roztyly, Budějovická, I.P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Now there are five in the city but by the end of the year there would have to be eighty," Opatrný added.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
Using the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Just enter the Opencard chip card in it and the previously paid bonus will be charged only on it.
The electronic bonds from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
That is, in circular trains and bus lines from the numbers 300 to 499 that are used mainly by inhabitants of central Bohemian towns.
“In the trains attached to Prague’s integrated transport there are reviewers equipped with a reader card that will help confirm the validity of the time and the zone of the voucher,” said Filip Drápal, the ticket control, of the Ropid organization that sets the timetables of Prague’s collective transport.
Circular buses have their reader cards mounted on the driver’s ticket box.
When entering it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver but also it is necessary to accompany it with the Opencard in the place intended for this on the side of the Box.
The driver controls the validity of the ticket.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonuses there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," Drápal added.
Passengers who do not travel on the circular buses and do not remember when the ticket expires can go to the dealer machines where the cards are recharged.
Here, on the machine screen, you will be shown information about the validity of your document.
