The first time it happens, you may get scared, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign sleep disorder called somnilochiae.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I’m sure more than one has told him that he spoke overnight.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in a lifetime, for example, associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause for its appearance.
Often they are related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (to get sick) or sleeping, but it has no reason to be so.
As we mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever, stressful situations or over-excitation.
This is a very little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
It may be that you speak in a quiet tone, loose words, a whimper or the opposite (crying, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him out of this way.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, therefore it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress picture).
What can be done is to consider a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to bed.
So look for quiet games and avoid programs or television series that are frightening or a bit violent.
With children who are very nervous and who find it hard to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will help the child to have a quieter sleep.
Once the somniloquies appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless for the child and that the next day he will not remember anything of what happened.
Useful Advice
Do not wake him.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Even though he is speaking, he is sleeping and therefore is resting.
Remember that if you are very anxious during several episodes, it would be advisable to consult or find out what generates so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what you say (which is not the most common thing), do not fall into the temptation to make an interrogation to give you information.
You won’t get anything, because when you’re asleep you’re not conscious how to organize your thinking.
Moreover, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say that, so be very careful in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell a child that you can question him at night to know his secrets.
Not even a joke.
That creates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don’t worry, it’s not bad, it’s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
