The Interview - Blood Is Safe Again
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained public confidence that had been seriously vacillated by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and the dissatisfaction of the public, the government of Canada made in February 1994 a public survey, chaired by judge Horacio Krever, intending to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations for such a disaster not to be repeated again.
While Judge Krever was delayed to present his relationship, certain provinces then created a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
As a result of Gélineau and Krever’s reports, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, recalls Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
After making a lot of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work over the years that followed, we have recovered public confidence,” he says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, 94% of the Quebec population had subsequent confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary reminds, however, that “confidence is something extremely fragile.”
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we witnessed in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Décary.
And we didn’t know if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
Then we rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know it and when a serious illness can emanate from it, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we impose exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had stayed in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been shown out of all doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
This episode showed us so that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests that allow to detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not the presence of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until now were based.
Nucleic acid tests have shortened the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period by less than a week.
This substantially reduces the risk of certain donors being infected without knowing it and being unable to detect them.
These improvements significantly lowered the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“This means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I believe that one can today receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without worrying,” says the head of management of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion that, for example, the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We need to be constantly vigilant,” Dr. Décary continues before emphasizing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient supply.
“The demands are increasing because the population is ageing.
As the most aggressive anti-cancer treatments, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences on the blood donor network that agglomerates on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation.
All persons with good health, aged 18 and who meet the eligibility criteria can however donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they traveled to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With this 3% we manage to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But members of this network of donors must be renewed as they get older and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to be a regular donor.
Since current life is very unrestricted, we rarely find the time to spend an hour donating their blood,” grieves Francine Décary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone envelopes, heart valves, eye balloons and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public umbilical blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood of stem cells that can be used for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
“We celebrated a few weeks ago, the putting on the bench of our thousandth sample of umbilical blood and is expected to take more than a thousand of these per year.
We should start proposing it for injections early next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood-taking program as very popular.
“Many moms are disappointed not being able to enjoy this,” as Héma-Québec lacks the resources to propose this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
