Wall Street rescue operation: Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most important economic bailout plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has shaken Wall Street for months has yet to be confirmed by both houses of Congress.
It provides in particular for: better control by the elected of its implementation, new mechanisms aimed at ensuring the refund of the public money invested, new provisions to contain the number of houses barred the lack of payment, as well as a right of taxation on wages paid to the leaders of the saved companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, at the end of a two-day marathon of negotiations.
“We have made great progress towards a deal that will be effective in the markets,” said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
“Everything has been done to cover up the economy and ordinary Americans in the face of the current Wall Street crisis,” she said.
"It's the fundamental point: if we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and disruptions on the daily lives of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had ended very quickly in the last few hours because they feared the effect that would provoke a new failure in the mood of investors.
The last time they had set was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates in the American presidential elections, who have joined the negotiations late, were rather favorable to the agreement, but did not forget to express their dissatisfaction with being forced to reach this extreme.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama was given certain arrangements to reach the agreement, the one that would allow owners to keep their homes and the one on the salary of the executives of state-supervised companies.
“When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no need to be congratulated.
But these measures are necessary,” he commented on American television.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, responded that: "I would like to see the details, but I hope to vote for it."
"The important points I read [show] that it is something we will have to digest and with which we can move forward.
He said the option of not doing anything is unacceptable.”
The $700 billion plan aims to buy from taxpayers’ money the dubious debts, risky assets and non-selling assets of American financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis provoked by the eruption of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risk mortgages before spreading to other more common forms of credit bonds (PCAAs) and provoked a freeze of liquidity and a breakdown of banks and financial institutions.
It is a group of elected Republicans who had changed the first draft agreement last week.
We believe we’ve come out of the stagnation since Democrats accepted that certain “toxic” assets from companies in trouble are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
With the aim of limiting the hardships for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision that stipulated that if the government had to assume losses for five years with this program, it could impose new rates that would aim to help it recover money.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first portion of $250 billion to which another $100 billion may be added if the president considers it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion would have to be confirmed by another congressional vote.
In exchange for their help, Washington will get shares in the rescued companies that will be worth dividends in case of profits and that will be able to re-sell when the storm is over.
The federal government will have the possibility to delay the procedures of embargoes concerning housing obtained with real estate loans under this plan, as well as to set limits on remuneration and on compensation paid to the leaders of the companies affected by the crisis.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to the voting of the House of Representatives from today and the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all his efforts, he is still not sure that his plan will be approved.
Some people continued to protest yesterday against this project, both on the part of the Republicans and Democrats.
Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, declared to his voters that "with all evidence, Washington does not want to understand."
“We have a very serious financial problem.
There are some solutions.
But not that which consists in taking advantage of the taxpayers.”
Democratic representative Brad Sherman, who is an animator of a small group in Congress, presents the problems differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred economics professors, including three Nobel Prize winners, wrote to us to tell us: we ask Congress not to rush and carefully examine the path to take,” he said.
At this same time, in Europe, we once again had the proof of the global nature of the crisis.
Following an urgent meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the banking group Fortis for €11.2 billion ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it had given up buying its bankrupt competitor since it lost €2.9 billion during the U.S. risk real estate loan crisis.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is part of the 20 largest European banks and the 10 largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said.
Instead, we have a right to vote and influence in the bank.
