Very soon, on 8 October, criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of committing fraud of significant harm, in a business manner, continuously and in an organized manner, in addition to other crimes, including the counterfeiting of documents.
According to the Prosecutor’s Office, the funds obtained in public contests were used for their own purposes, justifying in many cases the fulfillment of the tasks with false invoices.
Public funds and municipal funds – in total about 65 million HUF – were partly left in the treasury of the Fiatal Baloldal organization and partly in the pocket of private individuals.
The method, which was also made known by the researchers, was to justify the collection of funds obtained in public procurement with false invoices behind which there was no real execution, the different associations never fulfilled their obligations assumed.
According to the prosecution, most of the bills were fake.
To do this, the talonaries were obtained in the Józsefváros District market and the circular seals were manufactured in the city of Kiskunhalas.
And the question of which company to carry out the counterfeit invoice was decided, among others, on that tour of the Upper Balaton Region where János Zuschlag sent István Lados.
The latter confessed that for this purpose he had to choose hostels and restaurants.
He asked for invoice for his consumptions and these served as a model for the invoices they presented, among others, in the competitions of the Ministry of Youth and Sports Affairs, in the Ministry of Social and Labor Affairs, as well as in the City Council of the Capital.
These invoices were mostly signed by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who according to our information rather wrote the reports needed to obtain the public subsidies.
During one of his "study trips" Lados chose a brewery.
According to two invoices issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and his accomplices, this gastronomic center provided food for a group of ninety people from the Association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However – according to the center manager – so many people don’t fit in that place at the same time.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation – later called Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért – was filled with formal and contextual errors.
For a hostel in the town of Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms and more than ten people could not stay there in one night, however in the bill stood one hundred and thirty people.
But the fancy billmakers also exaggerated when they pointed out to the gastronomic center Pigal Kft. because in the bookstore of the same - according to the information given to the Prosecutor's Office - there were no documents on behalf of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, the manager of the company, informed hvg.hu that when he was quoted by the prosecutor’s office and shown the invoices, he already knew it was fake documents.
"On the seal the name of our company and the NIF appeared in the wrong place."
He added: in addition to the formal problems, he did not agree that according to the invoice, 100 people were housed, since they have only eleven rooms in which there are not so many people.
In addition, meals were included in the bill, while the restaurant has not been operating for a long time.
The enthusiastic bill makers were also not informed that the travel agency chosen in Budapest exclusively organized trips abroad, so that on the cash payment invoice they foolishly indicated a trip within Hungary as a service, which also did not coincide with the agency’s practice of invoicing.
In addition – as it was known during the investigation – they included VAT in the document as well, despite the fact that travel outside the territory of the European Union were exempt from taxes.
Among other things, the measurement of VAT was also incorrect in the four documents issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, since the services of that company are not charged with a 25 but only with 15 percent of VAT, in addition the hotel employees only issued machine-made invoices but the invoice was manual.
In addition, the "expedients" also committed other mistakes, such as in the case of a company in which they put on the invoice as an activity carried out by road to which - it was known during the investigations of the prosecutor's office - the company founded as an investment consultant does not.
Equally due to formal differences – inadequate format of the invoice, false seal – it was known that the invoices issued for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, for XXI.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó Sports Camp, whose representatives denied having issued those invoices.
The counterfeiters also did not pay attention to the fact that when the Fiatal Városért Egyesület group ate there (2001) the HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in the process of liquidation, so the liquidation process manager - according to our information - denied having issued such a document.
Consciously paying invoices
Another group of manufacturers of fake invoices are those who were aware that they had to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of Fiatal Baloldal – Ifjú Szocialisták, issued an invoice worth about four million HUF on behalf of the Együtt Foundation to Harmadik Évezredért.
The manager of Collab Kft. – according to the indictment – was persuaded by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi, to issue fictitious invoices.
Similarly, Biogate Kft., currently under liquidation, collaborated with Zuschlag and its accomplices, which in 2003 supplied invoices worth approximately five million HUF to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány, the Atlasz Egyesület and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület, with no real economic activity behind it.
There was no movement of capital either, because afterwards they canceled the prepared invoices but forgot to make this entity recorded in their documents.
The next group of manufacturers of fake invoices includes those who have some link with the accused.
For example, Ivan Kubatov was the plaintiff of the Ukrainian manager of the Delta Trio SL with a fictitious headquarters in Budapest, which dealt with fuel and vehicle trade.
This company issued numerous invoices worth approximately 18 million HUF in the months of October, November and December 2005 on the sale of computer media.
According to the investigation data, these bills were purchased by Cash Investment Kft. in Kiskunhalas, which has been under liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The manager of this company was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov should have dispatched the documents related to the company between 2002 and 2005.
We have information that Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued in the name of the company invoices for the Atlasz, for the Hoppá and for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, collecting the amount himself.
Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt. were founded by Romanian farmers at the express request of Ivan Kubatov.
