Who, on the other hand, for these days even could offend himself, since to ease his prison conditions he requested house arrest, but was repeatedly denied.
While the numerous perpetrators of very superior economic crimes, who have never returned the money, pass freely or at least can wait in their own home for the sentence, he has no possibility for that.
Overlapping Psychology: Why do we spend more money?
Participants in auctions are likely to spend more money and overvalu the product.
Neuroscientists and economists at the University of New York discovered the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to the study appeared in the journal Science, people don’t want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this “game” through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played lottery, the other participated in a auction and in the meantime the functional magnetic resonance imaging system (fMRI) examined the active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment.
In both games participants could earn money, but during auctions, where it is a fundamental element to bet more than the other, when losing the game intensified the functioning of the complex called stratum located beneath the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self-price" mechanism of the nervous system.
According to the scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention to not provoke an intense reaction of the layer.
To support their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment, three groups bet against one person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members made a bet.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive $15 more in prize.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction the members of the group lost even that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, checking the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winning" group.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previous economic theory.
Those who so far explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped solve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the University of New York School of Economics.
Hepatitis: When to go to the doctor?
In the world about five hundred million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of infected in this country is estimated at 100,000, but only seven thousand are treated because many of the sick do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the common name for various liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; liver infection and ictery are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses in dependence on the pathogen spread in two main forms: hepatitis A and E by food (e.g. with water or food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and with body moods (sperm, vagina mood, saliva).
It is recommended that travellers protect themselves against the A and B viruses; there are no vaccines against the C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, it is manifested by a general illness, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After this appear on the skin and in the white of the eyes yellowness, the feces become clear, the urine is dark and healing can last even two to three weeks.
Every year one million people die in the world from cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most severe forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten infected receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can cause liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Therefore, early detection and systematic medical check-up are very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and those who wear tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory check too, it is worth consulting with your family doctor if you experience any unknown symptoms.
The disease has cure if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so it can suppress the contagion and prevent cancer.
The 30th of September is World Hepatitis Day, which was organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their premature recognition.
Does it hurt those who believe in God?
According to the results of a recent research, religious faith has a calming effect that also relieved the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed how religious belief influences human pain, the British newspaper Telegraph.
In the context of this singular experiment, they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists, while all were looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the human brain scanning technique, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first of a series of researches in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University also participate alongside academics.
The analysis occurred as follows; they fixed a sparkle instrument to the patient’s left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look at two paintings; the Virgin Mary, a 17th-century work by Sassoferrato, and Leonardo da Vinci's 15th-century armor lady.
The researchers had the hope that the show of the Virgin Mary would provoke a certain religious encouragement among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it wasn't too different from the other, and thought it had a reassuring effect.
The patients spent half an hour on an MRI scanner, receiving during that period 20 electric shocks in four consecutive parts while observing the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics stated that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt “safe” as “protected” people, they “reassured themselves and peace reigned in their hearts.”
When they looked at the religious theme picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any such shocking image you can a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person for whom they feel very positively, like for a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
"The practice of faith should and in many cases truly changes our personality," Wright added.
After these formidable results there is only one question: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if the faithful were shown the Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of his size?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary bring even better results?
