But it may also be because geeks see with precision the very problematic relationship existing between human rights and the Internet that was produced precisely by one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: the Web 2.0.
The Web 2.0 is about collaboration, leaving intentional footprints behind us and taking advantage of the communication channels available, and while the measurements of these vary individually, the essence remains the same: showing ourselves.
A normal young person can have a profile on numerous collective pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and can even join them with other services, such as Twitter or last.fm that offers list of their music customs, then they can include them in a tracking system like FriendFeed or Blip.fm, can also have a blog, in which the most recent photo galleries that are stored on Flickr or Picasa appear automatically.
We can know numerous cases from which it arises that for example the girlfriend, by seeing the flow of photographs the next morning of common friends, finds out who spent the night before her fraudulent boyfriend or can dismiss the employee of a company because he writes his sincere opinion on his blog about the direction of the company: one thing is certain, the definition of privacy has been completely revalued.
A person’s “on-line” life is what he shows of himself – this is the definition that lies behind the behavior of today’s youth.
And whoever wants to hide something, or at least intends to evade the monopoly of Google, can do so (beginning for example with the Scroogle that uses the Google search system, but does not leave traces).
There are many people who do not want to register on the collective pages to avoid being able to find them, but they can replace Google's "on-line" applications, from text writing software to image and news reading apps with alternative versions which do not connect to gigantic servers or prepare the most perfect profile possible about us.
Public opinion is almost openly waiting for the day when Google will show its true face.
The company with its current value of $156 billion is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca-Cola (110 billion dollars), AdWords/AdSense advertising surfaces threaten the revenue of advertising agencies, while services that are increasingly rapidly introduced cause serious headaches not only for Microsoft, but also for numerous other software developers.
Critical observers, however, will find the alarming contradictions too: for example, the top management roughly rejected the employee protest after doubling the price of the company's nursery, considered too expensive the unlimited number of employees' feeding, but all this is nothing compared to the fact that in 2006 Google ceded to pressure from the Chinese government and the company under the agreement filed all information that violated the good morals and interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the company’s internal regulations says they won’t announce any new service in advance, but only when it was already ready to operate, which if it’s certain is that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years may revolve the World: while some believe that the scanning and archiving project of Google’s books and magazines will acquire such dimensions that the company will soon be quoted by the U.S. Supreme Court, others fear their Health system, because in it we can create our own complete health profile, with previous analyses, with our doctors and our problems.
And the fact that Google is going to create a genetic database can provide a good raw material for science fiction writers, Scroogled, the popular novel of Cory Doctorow, describes in Orwellian form that future, in which a man only from Google data can be described alarmingly well.
