The smart car imitates the flight of the bird
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of obstacle sensors existing in nature?
For example, those of the beetles.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the beetles provided the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the nature-imitating BR23C car robotic steering system, which was given the characteristics of beetles, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can evade all collisions.
During flight, each butterfly creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained at the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technology director of RP and development and research.
A major role is played by compound eyes that are able to see in all directions at a angle greater than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of compound eyes, the engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at a angle of 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the vehicle’s microprocessor that immediately turns into a manoeuvre to avoid the collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle robot imitating the movements of the beetles, changes the direction by turning the wheels to the necessary extent.
Unlike any existing system today, this manoeuvre is entirely instinctive.
“If it didn’t, the vehicle robot’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
You must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which currently all kinds of collisions are considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a beetle does to avoid other beetles.
This process should be done in an open and closed eye.
However, unlike beetles, the movement can not be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the endless possibilities that exist for the cockroaches to avoid other cockroaches, here they only used as a possibility for the car robot the rotating movement and acceleration as well as the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer life than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the important thing is instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the ability to process data, much less the ability to store it.
This device every second only needs to process some input signals and react accordingly.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of the previous manoeuvres, so it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
No gigabytes or megabytes are needed.
This is the first step to develop the technology to immediately evade obstacles, which according to Nissan’s calculations, within ten years will be able to be incorporated into mass-produced models.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding obstacles on his way.
