The written version of the law of the $700 billion financial bailout package has been prepared that will be applied in several phases with the purpose of buying bad credit from banks.
In the first phase, half of the money will be spent.
During the new consultations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, congressional leaders reached an agreement around the $700 billion financial bailout package in total, after several days of discussion, Reuters.
We’ve made significant progress,” said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic president of the US Congress, saying it’s just about to formalize the deal in a document.
The commitment on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Minister of Finance, speaking about the outcome of the compromise stated: this program will work and will be efficient but other measures are needed.
The written version of the package was released before the opening of Asian markets, i.e. Sunday before 8 p.m. on Washington time (i.e. before 2 p.m. on Monday, Central European time), without causing a spectacular leap in the stock markets.
On the draft law called the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilization Act, Monday will be voted first by the U.S. Congress and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also celebrated the news about the deal.
"We are pleased with the progress achieved overnight and highly appreciate both parties' efforts to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said.
The program is different from the Bush administration’s original proposal to spend all of the $700 billion to buy poor-quality credit fund securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion can be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, of this sum the Ministry of Finance will buy bad-rated credit fund securities and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president’s decision.
This program will be controlled by a special body, in which the president of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion could be spent after a new Congressional decision.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy bad loans, mortgages and credit fund securities, in addition to other "poison" type loans as well.
The purchase can be made at auctions or directly - informed competent persons of the ministry.
The law allows affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the financial portfolio guarantees the worrying elements, for which companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson stated that the law thus ensures the necessary financial means, that can even reach $700 billion to meet the urgent needs of the U.S. financial system, whether it be the purchase of bad financial means, their insurance or the prevention of risks that could cause the collapse of some large financial institutions.
We do everything necessary to be ready to introduce the law as soon as it is signed, he added.
Instead, the heads of the banks who are in trouble and waiting for state aid will be able to count on the official limitation of their compensations, which the American argot simply calls gold parachutes.
Only in certain cases will the payments be limited, and the limitations depend on the form of aid from the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry buys under an auction, an extra tax will be imposed on the gold parachutes, unless the bank’s failed chief is fired.
By directly buying bad loans, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that boss compensations are not exaggerated.
In addition to the above, existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, but restrictions will only apply to new contracts to stimulate participation in the program.
This is the first case in U.S. history in which a legal limitation on general directors' income will be in place, said Barney Frank, chairman of the Congressional committee responsible for financial services.
The State will also have the right to acquire shares of the banks participating in the program, so the risk of taxpayers will be reduced, as ultimately they will even be able to get profits from the transaction as soon as the economy and the bank recover.
According to the bill, in the next five years, the president will have to submit to Congress a proposal on how to reimburse the financial sector’s losses to taxpayers.
Of course, there were those on both sides who expressed their reservations regarding the project.
This is not what the American citizens have commissioned us, that is, they are not protecting the taxpayer’s dollars,” said California Republican congressman Darrell Issa.
His Ohio Democratic colleague Mary Kaptur said the measures were urged by those who are responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1% compared to last month’s prices and by 12.9% compared to August 2007 prices, the Central Statistical Office (KSH).
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 percent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 percent compared to the previous year.
As a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7% compared to the previous month and by 3.2% compared to the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only slightly, by 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry sectors increased slightly, by 0.1% compared to July.
The largest increase in the magnitude of prices occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 percent), due in the first place to the increase of 4.6 percent monthly of bags and belts and the increase of 2.5 percent of footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical materials production branch (1,6 percent).
There was a price decline in the petrochemical sector (1,4 percent), in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimal extent - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 percent).
Prices for paper manufacturing, publishing and printing did not change.
In the other sectors of the processing industry, prices increased between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water, which represent an important weight within the domestic trade, a 0.3% increase was recorded in August, primarily as a result of the effect of the rise in official prices from July 1.
In a twelve-month comparison – in the domestic sales of the processing sectors – the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metal industry there was an increase of 13.2 percent, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of determining weight, there was an increase of 11 percent.
Prices fell in the textile industry (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacturing of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the rest of the processing sectors the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Over the past year in the processing industry globally prices increased by 10.2 percent.
The prices of electricity, gas, heat and water supplies exceeded the prices of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In the month of August, among the different sectors of domestic trade the largest monthly price increase ( 0.7 percent) was recorded in the sectors of investment goods.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 percent, and in the energy sector and intermediate sectors there were no changes compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, with respect to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 percent).
Branches producing consumer goods declined by 6.8 percent and investment goods by 1.4 percent.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF increased 1.1 percent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decline of 3.9 percent.
The quotation of our national currency in one month decreased by 1.7 per cent with respect to the euro and by 7.1 per cent with respect to the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 per cent with respect to the euro and 15.9 per cent with respect to the dollar.
