The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken.
Today the European Summit for Equal Opportunities has begun in Paris, its host is France, which this year is also the turn president of the European Union.
Lívia Járóka, member of the European People’s Party for the Fidesz, in her message to the plenary, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that strike Roma children and is also the biggest obstacle to the prevailing foundation of their interests.
This high-level conference was inaugurated – on behalf of the French Presidency – by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister of Employment and Social Affairs, and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the leading European organizations for the protection of social rights attended the meeting.
Járóka - according to the press office of the Fidesz group of MEPs in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, Roma are left out of the labour market primarily because of their low schooling level.
“The majority of young Roma have not completed secondary education and due to the poor quality of basic education, only an insignificant portion can obtain a university diploma.”
Járóka also pointed out that education, as a fundamental human right, has a determining role in the prevailing foundation of other human rights as well.
Investing in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economies of the EU Member States.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these issues widely, both among Roma and among non-Gypsy.
The sooner a Romanian student starts school, the more chances they will have to become an active member of the labor market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
“The Roma, as citizens of the European Union, must be assured of the right to quality education and guaranteed the abolition of segregated and low-level education,” said Lívia Járóka.
The objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary to immediately accelerate the processes of school segregation, for which the correct compliance with existing and planned anti-discrimination directives is of fundamental importance.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we must offer Roma children the possibility that guarantees the democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full-fledged citizens," Járóka said.
The aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, organized annually since the Berlin meeting last year, which was held in the sign of the “European Year of Equal Opportunities”, is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at the European and national level of the Member States.
