The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore photographs effectively what is happening in the major Italian urban centers and also in the province cities.
The process of marginalization of the cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticons in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear almost always are historical places, full of memory,"it is as if a friend died, a friend with whom a piece of place and so much emotion was shared," Observes the director of the new cinema Paradise, the film that twenty years ago won the cousin Oscar and the grand prize of the jury at Cannes, which told the poetry of a provincial cinema room and the nostalgia for the way of living the cinema that lost forever.
The figures given by Anec, the main association of merchants, are clear: in the past five years, 316 traditional cinemas have been closed, and the majority are paid for the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are first, Emilia-Romaña with 82 cinemas less, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the responsible for their disappearance is the advance of the multiplex, they are own these three Italian regions that have registered the largest number of new meticons cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romaña.
“The Italian exercise has developed irrationally,” observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, “it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to guarantee the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all of its frequenters are willing to transfer to the meticons.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favor of traders: the previous debt of the state is approximately 10 million euros.
It is shameful from an ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To support the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year.”
Interesting the case of Bologna, the first Italian city to worry about the closures, decided to repair with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of this type in Italy to promote and protect the mono-sala cinema in the historic center and on the periphery.
Among the rules foreseen are mediated tax facilitations in favor of managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the traffic-limited zone and will have special rates for parking.
“It’s an initiative that I like,” observes Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting other measures in place.
It is true, that to contrast the extra power of meticons, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the audience today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Bagheria cinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to do the "New Paradise cinema", which I had already thought about 10 years ago.
I’ve lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I go in front of the Rialto or Quirinale de Via Nazionale already closed, where I’ve lived so many emotions shared, not to see the posters darkened by dust, I turn to the other side.”
