When the energy comes from the waves, the great ones come down to the stage.
It is an extinct site that occupies more than 70% of the planet’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which the big ones like Chevron look.
The possibility of harvesting energy from sea movements has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s, along with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil was low, in 1980, the idea of leveraging marine energy was rejected, but now that environmental cases and the new rise of oil give momentum to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London has estimated that by 2007 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by implants that exploit the movement of sea waves.
This would be twice as much as the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And there would also be the streams and the tide.
Giants in attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy has been Enersis, which in 2005 has sealed an agreement to build an implant in the North of Portugal.
When the intention was announced it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years away to bet on marine energy are always more and among these companies the ones who have always voted for traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying technology on ocean energy,” a spokesman for a company associated with the US oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, “and is evaluating the possibility of cooperating with us.”
The cooperation in question is about obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, to carry out a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
It’s a pretty important signal, considering that in Alaska the US continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has activated a plan to carry out new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. in New York and Ocean Power in New Jersey are following the path of energy coming from the sea, the total invested so far, although no details indicate an increasing interest.
Technology to develop.
Experts speak of a technology still in the beginning, because marine energy has no doubt that it has a great impact on the environment.
For now, impacts such as those of the Portuguese or the Scots are of small size and do not seem to create big problems to the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a long scale, a technology with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the options are several: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of goods joined between them.
The force of the waves, which makes the goods move up and down becomes hydraulic pressure with pistons and cylinders inside them.
The pressure causes a turbine to spin, which in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent to the coast through submarine cables.
For now there are four implants of this type under development, waiting only for federal approval, apart from energy, could serve for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, is already producing power for a shopping mall and a parking lot, using submarine turbines on the East River of New York.
The movement of water when there are tide, makes the pallets of the turbines turn, creating a rotating movement that feeds the generator.
Verdant has said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to use the energy.
